policies, representations, and the impact on local communities more generally. Combining case-studies and theoretical reflections, the volume’s contributions engage with a variety of topics and disciplinary perspectives yet also with several common themes. One revolves around problems of definition, both in terms of demarcating cities from their surroundings and of distinguishing migration in a narrower sense from other forms of short- and long-distance mobility. Further shared concerns include the integration of multiple analytical scales, contextual factors, and diachronic variables (such as urbanization, industrialization, and the digital revolution).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 4aEuropäische Geschichte. 4aMigration. 4aMobilität. 4aStadtgeschichte. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aMigration, Mobility, Urban History, European History.1 aAlthammer, Beate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunnström, Pål, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornelissen, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornelißen, Christoph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCreyghton, Camille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDo Paço, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHackett, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHahn, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKümin, Beat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKümin, Beat, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeggewie, Claus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuzzi, Serena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.